ndus and Sikhs from South Asia; Buddhist organizations from Southeast Asia; and Tibetan, Japanese, and Chinese religions from East and Central Asia. Although the geographical focus is particular, the conceptual focus is broad – the authors explore each religious tradition in the larger context of Canadian multiculturalism. As the first comprehensive and comparative examination of Asian religions in British Columbia, this book is mandatory reading for teachers, policy makers, scholars of British Columbia history and Asian Canadian studies, or anyone who wants to be well informed about this province and nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh1 aBaird, Ian G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Don, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCrowe, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeVries, Larry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeVries, Larry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJardins, Marc Des, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacLean, Derryl N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMadanayake, Bandu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMehri, Rastin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNayar, Kamala Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewton, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOvermyer, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOvermyer, Dan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.